<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08038h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08038h">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08038h"> 38(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> threw dirty tobacco spits / handcuffed / Sandy Row / Specials / food was rough / snow drifted <font color="green">[in on]</font> top of bed</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Mr. Cahir Healy, M. P. Again Arrested</b> Mr. Cahir Healy, M. P., was re-arrested at Enniskillen yesterday as he was leaving for Dublin for having entered the western area of Fermanagh in defiance of the Northern Prohibition Order.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <font color="green">[A Jeering Crowd / Belfast Indignities]</font> Mr. Healy stated that he was arrested on May 22, 1922, and brought to the military barracks in Enniskillen with about 60 other prisoners <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> After some days in Enniskillen barracks 14 of the men arrested were released, the remaining 46 being transferred to Crumlin Road Jail, Belfast.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> All the time they were <mark>handcuffed</mark> in pairs. / A large hostile crowd gathered from <mark>Sandy Row</mark>, immediately adjoining the station premises <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Mr. Healy continued, &ldquo;at least two men in the crowd <mark>threw dirty tobacco spits on me</mark>, and I saw the same treatment meted out to other prisoners. We were piled on two lorries like sacks of mails, with <mark>Specials</mark> sitting all round the outer edges <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font>&rdquo; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> On Nov. 22 last the prisoners were removed <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> in two batches&mdash;one going to Crumlin Road Jail and the other to Larne Union buildings. Mr. Healy was among those removed to Larne where most of the rooms were without any heating apparatus.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The windows in the building were broken, and in the snowy weather of January <mark>snow frequently drifted in on top of the beds</mark>.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The <mark>food was rough</mark> and was never varied. <small> <a name="II13feb23" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#II13feb23"><cite title="source">Irish Independent</cite></a> (13 February 1923) 7/1-2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Cahir Healy (1877-1970) was Sinn Fe&eacute;in M.P. for Westminster. His account of prison conditions was also published in an influential series of articles in the <i>Daily Express</i>, which helped bring about the release of the internees. </mm> </dd></dl>
